From 354d440d40ffde1a3f311071b46ed51fc5b7b149 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Johannes Schindelin <johannes.schindelin@gmx.de>
Date: Wed, 6 May 2026 09:45:38 +0200
Subject: [PATCH 11/25] tests: cover the expr builtin

Add tests/expr.tests, tests/expr.right and tests/run-expr to
exercise every operator and named operation supported by the new
expr builtin: arithmetic (+, -, *, /, %, parentheses, signed
overflow into intmax_t), the six comparison operators with both
the numeric and the lexical paths, the short-circuiting | and &,
the `:' regex match (with and without a \( \) capture group, both
matching and non-matching), length, substr (including the
out-of-range edge cases POSIX requires to return ""), index and
match.  Each test prints its result through a helper that also
prints the exit status, so the .right file pins down both.

The error-case tests deliberately suppress stderr and check only
the exit status, so that the same expectations match the builtin
and /usr/bin/expr; this was used during development to confirm
that the builtin is bug-compatible with GNU coreutils' expr on
every observable behavior the test exercises (verified by
substituting `enable -n expr' for the keyword-loading line and
re-running, then diffing the captured outputs -- they were
identical).

Assisted-by: Claude Opus 4.7
Signed-off-by: Johannes Schindelin <johannes.schindelin@gmx.de>
